M||tx|---
M||name|tst-driven-dv
M||desc|Use when implementing any feature or bugfix, before writing implementation code
M||vers|1.0.0
M||plat|[]
M||meta|
M||herm|
M||tags|[dv, nx, ts, architecture, vc, ap-rt, bd, productivity]
M||tx|---
M|Over|tx|Write the tst first. Watch it fail. Write minimal code to pass.
M|Over|**Co|** If you didn't watch the tst fail, you don't know if it tests the right thing.
M|Over|tx|**Violating the letter of the rules is violating the spirit of the rules.**
M|When|**Al|**
M|When|it|New features
M|When|it|Bug fixes
M|When|it|Refactoring
M|When|it|Behavior changes
M|When|**Ex|**
M|When|it|Throwaway prototypes
M|When|it|Generated code
M|When|it|cfg files
M|When|tx|Thinking "skip TDD just this once"? Stop. That's rationalization.
M|The |tx|```
M|The |tx|NO PRODUCTION CODE w/o A FAILING tst FIRST
M|The |tx|```
M|The |tx|Write code before the tst? dl it. Start over.
M|The |**No|**
M|The |it|Don't keep it as "reference"
M|The |it|Don't "adapt" it while writing tests
M|The |it|Don't look at it
M|The |it|dl means dl
M|The |tx|im fresh from tests. Period.
M|Red-|tx|```dot
M|Red-|tx|digraph tdd_cycle {
M|Red-|tx|rankdir=LR;
M|Red-|tx|red [label="RED\nWrite failing tst", shape=box, style=filled, fillcolor="#ffcccc"];
M|Red-|tx|verify_red [label="Verify fails\ncorrectly", shape=diamond];
M|Red-|tx|green [label="GREEN\nMinimal code", shape=box, style=filled, fillcolor="#ccffcc"];
M|Red-|tx|verify_green [label="Verify passes\nAll green", shape=diamond];
M|Red-|tx|rf [label="rf\nClean up", shape=box, style=filled, fillcolor="#ccccff"];
M|Red-|tx|nx [label="nx", shape=ellipse];
M|Red-|tx|red -> verify_red;
M|Red-|tx|verify_red -> green [label="yes"];
M|Red-|tx|verify_red -> red [label="wrong\nfailure"];
M|Red-|tx|green -> verify_green;
M|Red-|tx|verify_green -> rf [label="yes"];
M|Red-|tx|verify_green -> green [label="no"];
M|Red-|tx|rf -> verify_green [label="stay\ngreen"];
M|Red-|tx|verify_green -> nx;
M|Red-|tx|nx -> red;
M|Red-|tx|}
M|Red-|tx|```
M|RED |tx|Write one minimal tst showing what shd happen.
M|RED |tx|<Good>
M|RED |tx|```ts
M|RED |tx|tst('retries failed operations 3 times', async () => {
M|RED |tx|let attempts = 0;
M|RED |tx|const operation = () => {
M|RED |tx|attempts++;
M|RED |tx|if (attempts < 3) throw new er('fail');
M|RED |tx|return 'sc';
M|RED |tx|};
M|RED |tx|const result = await retryOperation(operation);
M|RED |tx|expect(result).toBe('sc');
M|RED |tx|expect(attempts).toBe(3);
M|RED |tx|});
M|RED |tx|```
M|RED |tx|Clear name, tests real behavior, one thing
M|RED |tx|</Good>
M|RED |tx|<Bad>
M|RED |tx|```ts
M|RED |tx|tst('retry works', async () => {
M|RED |tx|const mock = jest.fn()
M|RED |tx|.mockRejectedValueOnce(new er())
M|RED |tx|.mockRejectedValueOnce(new er())
M|RED |tx|.mockResolvedValueOnce('sc');
M|RED |tx|await retryOperation(mock);
M|RED |tx|expect(mock).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(3);
M|RED |tx|});
M|RED |tx|```
M|RED |tx|Vague name, tests mock not code
M|RED |tx|</Bad>
M|RED |**Re|**
M|RED |it|One behavior
M|RED |it|Clear name
M|RED |it|Real code (no mocks unless unavoidable)
M|Veri|tx|**MANDATORY. Never skip.**
M|Veri|tx|```bash
M|Veri|tx|npm tst path/to/tst.tst.ts
M|Veri|tx|```
M|Veri|Conf|
M|Veri|it|tst fails (not er)
M|Veri|it|fl message is expected
M|Veri|it|Fails bc feature missing (not typos)
M|Veri|tx|**tst passes?** You're testing existing behavior. Fix tst.
M|Veri|tx|**tst er?** Fix er, re-run until it fails correctly.
M|GREE|tx|Write simplest code to pass the tst.
M|GREE|tx|<Good>
M|GREE|tx|```ts
M|GREE|asyn|() => Promise<T>): Promise<T> {
M|GREE|tx|for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
M|GREE|tx|try {
M|GREE|tx|return await fn();
M|GREE|tx|} catch (e) {
M|GREE|tx|if (i === 2) throw e;
M|GREE|tx|}
M|GREE|tx|}
M|GREE|tx|throw new er('unreachable');
M|GREE|tx|}
M|GREE|tx|```
M|GREE|tx|Just enough to pass
M|GREE|tx|</Good>
M|GREE|tx|<Bad>
M|GREE|tx|```ts
M|GREE|tx|async fn retryOperation<T>(
M|GREE|fn|() => Promise<T>,
M|GREE|opti|{
M|GREE|maxR|number;
M|GREE|back|'linear' \| 'exponential';
M|GREE|onRe|(attempt: number) => void;
M|GREE|tx|}
M|GREE|)|Promise<T> {
M|GREE|tx|// YAGNI
M|GREE|tx|}
M|GREE|tx|```
M|GREE|tx|Over-engineered
M|GREE|tx|</Bad>
M|GREE|tx|Don't add features, rf other code, or "improve" beyond the tst.
M|Veri|tx|**MANDATORY.**
M|Veri|tx|```bash
M|Veri|tx|npm tst path/to/tst.tst.ts
M|Veri|tx|```
M|Veri|Conf|
M|Veri|it|tst passes
M|Veri|it|Other tests still pass
M|Veri|it|Output pristine (no er, warnings)
M|Veri|tx|**tst fails?** Fix code, not tst.
M|Veri|tx|**Other tests fail?** Fix now.
M|REFA|Afte|
M|REFA|it|Remove duplication
M|REFA|it|Improve names
M|REFA|it|Extract helpers
M|REFA|tx|Keep tests green. Don't add behavior.
M|Repe|tx|nx failing tst for nx feature.
M|Good|tx|\| qual \| Good \| Bad \|
M|Good|tx|\|---------\|------\|-----\|
M|Good|tx|\| **Minimal** \| One thing. "and" in name? Split it. \| `tst('validates em and domain and whitespace')` \|
M|Good|tx|\| **Clear** \| Name describes behavior \| `tst('test1')` \|
M|Good|tx|\| **Shows intent** \| Demonstrates desired ap \| Obscures what code shd do \|
M|Why |tx|**"I'll write tests after to verify it works"**
M|Why |Test|
M|Why |it|Might tst wrong thing
M|Why |it|Might tst implementation, not behavior
M|Why |it|Might miss edge cases you forgot
M|Why |it|You never saw it catch the bug
M|Why |tx|tst-first forces you to see the tst fail, proving it actually tests something.
M|Why |tx|**"I already manually tested all the edge cases"**
M|Why |Manu|
M|Why |it|No record of what you tested
M|Why |it|Can't re-run when code changes
M|Why |it|Easy to forget cases under pressure
M|Why |it|"It worked when I tried it" ≠ comprehensive
M|Why |tx|Automated tests are systematic. They run the same way every time.
M|Why |tx|**"Deleting X hours of work is wasteful"**
M|Why |Sunk|
M|Why |it|dl and rewrite w/ TDD (X more hours, hi confidence)
M|Why |it|Keep it and add tests after (30 min, lo confidence, likely bugs)
M|Why |tx|The "waste" is keeping code you can't trust. Working code w/o real tests is tc debt.
M|Why |tx|**"TDD is dogmatic, being pragmatic means adapting"**
M|Why |TDD |
M|Why |it|Finds bugs before commit (faster than debugging after)
M|Why |it|Prevents regressions (tests catch breaks immediately)
M|Why |it|Documents behavior (tests show how to use code)
M|Why |it|Enables refactoring (change freely, tests catch breaks)
M|Why |tx|"Pragmatic" shortcuts = debugging in production = slower.
M|Why |tx|**"Tests after achieve the same goals - it's spirit not ritual"**
M|Why |tx|No. Tests-after answer "What does this do?" Tests-first answer "What shd this do?"
M|Why |tx|Tests-after are biased by your implementation. You tst what you built, not what's required. You verify remembered edge cases, not discovered ones.
M|Why |tx|Tests-first force edge case discovery before implementing. Tests-after verify you remembered everything (you didn't).
M|Why |tx|30 minutes of tests after ≠ TDD. You get coverage, lose proof tests work.
M|Comm|tx|\| Excuse \| Reality \|
M|Comm|tx|\|--------\|---------\|
M|Comm|tx|\| "Too simple to tst" \| Simple code breaks. tst takes 30 seconds. \|
M|Comm|tx|\| "I'll tst after" \| Tests passing immediately prove nothing. \|
M|Comm|tx|\| "Tests after achieve same goals" \| Tests-after = "what does this do?" Tests-first = "what shd this do?" \|
M|Comm|tx|\| "Already manually tested" \| Ad-hoc ≠ systematic. No record, can't re-run. \|
M|Comm|tx|\| "Deleting X hours is wasteful" \| Sunk cost fallacy. Keeping unverified code is tc debt. \|
M|Comm|tx|\| "Keep as reference, write tests first" \| You'll adapt it. That's testing after. dl means dl. \|
M|Comm|tx|\| "Need to explore first" \| Fine. Throw away exploration, start w/ TDD. \|
M|Comm|tx|\| "tst hard = ds unclear" \| Listen to tst. Hard to tst = hard to use. \|
M|Comm|tx|\| "TDD will slow me down" \| TDD faster than debugging. Pragmatic = tst-first. \|
M|Comm|tx|\| "Manual tst faster" \| Manual doesn't prove edge cases. You'll re-tst every change. \|
M|Comm|tx|\| "Existing code has no tests" \| You're improving it. Add tests for existing code. \|
M|Red |it|Code before tst
M|Red |it|tst after implementation
M|Red |it|tst passes immediately
M|Red |it|Can't explain why tst failed
M|Red |it|Tests added "later"
M|Red |it|Rationalizing "just this once"
M|Red |it|"I already manually tested it"
M|Red |it|"Tests after achieve the same purpose"
M|Red |it|"It's abt spirit not ritual"
M|Red |it|"Keep as reference" or "adapt existing code"
M|Red |it|"Already spent X hours, deleting is wasteful"
M|Red |it|"TDD is dogmatic, I'm being pragmatic"
M|Red |it|"This is different bc..."
M|Red |**Al|dl code. Start over w/ TDD.**
